<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ920304-0033</DOCNO><DOCID>920304-0033.</DOCID><HL>   Toronto Exchange Trading   Halted by Computer Woes</HL><DATE>03/04/92</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><MS>FINANCIAL (FIN)TECHNOLOGY (TEC)</MS><IN>COMPUTERS AND INFORMATION TECHNOLOGY (CPR)SECURITIES (SCR)</IN><RE>CANADA (CN)NORTH AMERICA (NME)</RE><LP>   TORONTO -- Stock trading on the floor of the Toronto StockExchange was halted for four hours yesterday when troublewith new computer software caused garbled and incompleteorders.   Volume on the exchange was 19.6 million shares, comparedwith this year's daily average of 30.6 million shares.</LP><TEXT>   Brokers shifted some of their trades to other exchanges.Volume on the Montreal Exchange was 12.7 million shares, morethan double the daily average.   &quot;I don't think any brokers suffered, I think most went tothe Montreal Exchange to trade for their clients,&quot; saidMurray Gregga, a senior vice president at ScotiaMcLeod Inc.   Toronto exchange officials halted equities-floor trading30 minutes into the session, when traders complained ofgarbled and incomplete orders appearing on the floor'scomputer screens. The halt affected about 800 stocks tradedon the floor of the exchange. It didn't affect trading of 800stocks on the exchange's Computer Assisted Trading System orfloor trading of futures and options.   John Thornton, vice president of markets and marketdevelopment for the Toronto exchange, said the trouble wastraced to changes made to computer software over the weekendas part of a move to eliminate equities-floor trading byearly next year. He said that trading resumed after thechanges were removed from the software.   &quot;We'll probably sort out the trades by the end of(Wednesday) but finding out what the problem is with theprogram will take a couple of weeks, &quot; said Mr. Thornton.</TEXT></DOC>